    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our offensive engine is built on exploiting favorable matchups against arms with high expected ERAs, led by **Tyler Freeman** and **Lawrence Butler**. **Tyler Freeman** (70.04) represents the most efficient play, buoyed by a prime #2 spot and a matchup against a soft Buehler delivery that creates a 90% probability for a stolen base\u2014our scarcest category. Meanwhile, **Lawrence Butler** (73.28) carries the highest score on the board, leveraging the leadoff position and a strong platoon advantage against the opposition. We are also capitalizing on a massive park factor boost in Tampa; **Matt Chapman** (69.96) and **Luis Arraez** (69.15) are both set to feast, with the latter\u2019s elite contact profile perfectly suited to the conditions, while **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (72.15) remains the anchor of our lineup, providing consistent, high-floor production regardless of minor fluctuations in his platoon splits against Elder.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was leaving **Brendan Donovan** (60.85) out of the starting nine. While his score is respectable and suggests he is a viable start, he fell just short of the efficiency threshold when compared to the ceiling of our current OF and MI configuration. With **Jeremiah Jackson** and **Daulton Varsho** offering better paths to scoring upside\u2014specifically regarding speed and situational platoon matchups\u2014**Brendan Donovan** remains our primary emergency depth. We are also monitoring the lineup status for **Will Smith**, **Cal Raleigh**, and **Tyler Freeman**; while their scores assume their projected spots in the order, any shuffle downward in the lineup will necessitate a quick re-evaluation of their efficiency metrics. Caution is advised with **Jeremiah Jackson**, as his score suffers from a bottom-of-the-order assignment that limits his plate appearance volume, though we are comfortable with the gamble given the overall team configuration.",
